#Need to figure out normalization for phosphoproteomics data

#Other normalization techniques are used for TMT-labeled phosphoproteomics data?
#Aside from median normalization, several other techniques are used to address 
#systemic biases and batch effects in TMT-labeled phosphoproteomics data. 
#These range from simple scaling to advanced statistical algorithms:
#  1. Quantile Normalization - more aggressive technique that forces the 
#distribution of intensities in each TMT channel to be identical. 

#Best for: Highly heterogeneous samples where median centering 
#alone may not align the data sufficiently.
#Caution: It can sometimes "over-correct" and reduce biological variation if 
#the underlying sample distributions are actually different due to experimental conditions. 

#2. Internal Reference Scaling (IRS)
#IRS is specifically designed for multi-plex TMT experiments where samples 
#are spread across multiple TMT kits. 
#It uses a common "bridge" sample (often a pool of all samples) included in every 
#multiplexed set.
#It corrects for the random MS2 sampling that occurs between different 
#mass spectrometry runs, effectively removing batch effects. 

#3. Total Peptide/Sum Normalization
#This method scales each channel so that the total sum of reporter ion intensities 
#is equal across all channels. 
#Logic: It assumes that the total amount of peptide material should be the 
#same in every channel.
#Pros/Cons: It is simple to implement but, like mean normalization,
#can be heavily influenced by a few extremely high-intensity peptides. 

#2 and 3 = probably already done after ms maxquant software. 3 was definitely already done.

#4. Variance Stabilizing Normalization (VSN)
#VSN transforms the data to make the variance constant across the entire range of intensities. 
#It uses a model that combines a linear transformation with a log-like transformation
#to account for both additive and multiplicative noise. 

#5. TAMPOR (Tukey’s Median Polish)
#TAMPOR is an extension of median normalization that uses an iterative 
#"median polish" algorithm. 
#It is highly robust to outliers and is particularly effective at removing batch effects
#while preserving biological signal in complex clinical datasets. 

#6. Loading Normalization (SL-TMT "Label Check")
#In "Streamlined TMT" (SL-TMT) workflows, a small aliquot of the labeled peptides 
#is run as a "label check" before the final pooling. 
#Process: Normalization factors are calculated from this preliminary run to adjust
#the final mixing volumes of each channel, ensuring a 1:1 ratio before the actual
#enrichment and deep-scale analysis. 

# Here we will experiment with median and quantile normalization.

#Log-transform first if your normalization method works better on log-scale (median, quantile).

