#1. Setting Up the Boundary 
#(for (i in 1:nrow(pprot_norm)))nrow(pprot_norm) counts the total number of rows 
#in your phosphoprotein dataset.1:nrow(...) creates a sequence of numbers from 1 
#up to that total row count.i is a counter variable. 
#The loop runs over and over, changing i to 1 on the first run, 2 on the second run,
#3 on the third run, and so on, until it hits the final row.
#2. Finding the Matching Total Protein 
#(acc <- pprot_norm$Accession[i])In every iteration, R looks at the current row ([i]) 
#of your phosphoprotein table and extracts the protein ID from the Accession column.
#It saves this ID to a temporary variable called acc (e.g., "O43719").
#3. Fetching and Subtracting the Data 
#(pprot_norm[i, common_cols] - totalprot[acc, common_cols])
#This is the core mathematical operation. 
#On the right side of the arrow:pprot_norm[i, common_cols]:
#Pulls the values for your specific samples (defined in common_cols) 
#for the current row i.totalprot[acc, common_cols]: Uses the protein ID (acc) 
#to jump directly to the matching row in your totalprot dataframe, 
#pulling the baseline protein expression values for those exact same samples.
#The Minus Sign (-): R subtracts the total protein values from the phosphoprotein 
#values across all sample columns simultaneously.\
#4. Overwriting the Data (pprot_norm[i, common_cols] <- ...)
#Finally, the left side of the arrow takes the brand-new, subtracted numbers and 
#saves them directly back into row i of your pprot_norm dataframe, 
